Pages = {1379-1384},
Month = {NOV},
Abstract = {The study aimed at determining the quality of life (QOL) of caregivers
   of stroke survivors in a Nigeria population and some patient and
   caregiver-related variables that may be associated with it.
   A survey of the QOL of volunteering informal caregivers of stroke
   survivors in purposively selected tertiary health centres from
   South-Eastern Nigeria was done using the SF-12 questionnaire.
   Caregivers rated their QOL fairly well. Older age, female gender and
   closeness in relationship to survivor were caregivers' variables that
   were significantly related to poorer QOL scores. Being a woman close
   relative is associated with lower mental health scores while being an
   older close relative contributed to lower physical health score (P <
   0.05). Caregivers' scores on the physical and mental health domains
   correlated moderately with each other (r = 0.52) and highly with their
   overall QOL scores (r = 0.81 and 0.88).
   Caring for stroke survivors in Nigeria seems to have adverse effects on
   the QOL of closer relatives who are either women or older. There is a
   need for clinicians to help those caregivers at risk find ways of
   improving and optimizing their QOL.},
