Pages = {128-133},
Abstract = {Background and Purposes: Primary informal caregivers play a significant
   role in providing care to stroke survivors after having been discharged
   from the hospital. Our aims were to describe the characteristics of Thai
   stroke caregivers and to explore their needs while providing care to
   their stroke relatives. Methods: Using open-ended questions, we
   individually interviewed 20 caregivers of stroke survivors to identify
   their characteristics and their own needs. Additional field notes were
   made during all interviews. Results: Our findings revealed that the
   majority of Thai informal stroke caregivers in this study were female,
   mostly daughters, with the exception of 2 Thai primary stroke caregivers
   found to be nieces. The majority of caregivers provided care to their
   stroke relatives 24 h per day. The four major categories of informal
   rehabilitation were: physical, psychological, social, and spiritual
   rehabilitation activities. Assistance, information and social support
   were the three main needs of the caregivers. Conclusion: Based on these
   findings, appropriate nursing information and assistance focusing on
   rehabilitation and stroke caregivers' needs should be provided to Thai
   stroke caregivers performing informal care to ensure that both patients
   and caregivers have the best possible quality of life. Copyright (c)
