Abstract = {Objective: This study examined whether spousal confidence in
   care-recipient recovery can predict recovery from activity limitations
   following stroke and how spousal confidence relates to stroke survivor
   self-efficacy for recovery. Design: A prospective design was used.
   Measures were gathered from stroke survivor/spouse dyads at two time
   points, both postdischarge from the hospital following stroke (N = 109).
   Main outcome measures: The dependent variable was recovery from
   ambulatory activity limitations over 6 weeks, as measured by the
   Functional Limitations Profile. A single spousal confidence item was
   tailored to an ambulatory behavior that the stroke survivors could not
   perform at Time 1. Results: Spousal confidence was correlated with
   ambulation recovery (r = -0.23, p <.05) and stroke survivor
   self-efficacy for recovery (r =.25, p <.05). Higher spousal confidence
   was associated with a better recovery and greater stroke survivor
   self-efficacy for recovery, but not with initial health status or
   practical support received. Conclusion: The relationship between
   caregiver confidence, care-recipient self-efficacy for recovery, and
   recovery outcomes needs further elucidation.},
