   problems after stroke, the majority of stroke survivors do not quit
   smoking. This may be due in part to the high rate of smoking among
   committed partners of stroke survivors. This study investigated the
   experiences of 11 dual-smoker stroke survivor-caregiver dyads,
   identifying themes which may be useful for understanding this entrenched
   population: managing the addiction as a dyad; conflicting feelings about
   whether smoking is an individual versus mutual concern; and dyad-level
   barriers and facilitators of quitting. We also present specific
   cessation strategies that dual-smoker dyads participating in the study
