   informal caregivers. This study focuses on the intensive intervention
   period of 3 months of an individualized mainly telephone-based
   problem-solving training for informal carers of stroke survivors
   (TIPS-Study). We present data of 47 strained caregivers who cared for
   their spouses and partners (n = 42) or (grand-) parents (n = 5). Results
   show that effective changes in burden can be achieved with only few
   contacts concentrating on problems that can be controlled by
   problem-focused coping mechanisms. Problems that require emotion-focused
   coping were processed rarely. Future perspectives of the approach are
