Volume = {20},
Number = {4},
Pages = {227+},
Month = {DEC},
Abstract = {Background: Relatives who care for stroke survivors at home provide
   extensive emotional, social and physical care, which can be perceived as
   a burden. Literature reveals inconsistencies in predicting caregivers'
   subjective burden. Objectives: The purpose of this analysis was to
   identify predictors of caregivers' subjective burden in a German
   population of caregivers of stroke patients. Method: We analyzed data
   from a subsample of caregivers of stroke patients (N = 466) from a
   larger cross sectional German study. We built a structural equation
   model, including patient, caregiver and situation characteristics as
   predictor variables and subjective burden as the outcome variable.
   Subjective burden was measured with the Burden Scale for Family
   Caregivers. Results: Caregivers are at higher risk to develop burden
   when they are younger, their own health status is poor, the workload is
   high or the patients' behavior has changed. The strongest predictor of
   caregiver burden was the caregivers' negative appraisal of the
   caregiving situation that correlated with feelings of being pressured
   into caregiving or not being oneself. The predictive relationship of
   nocturnal workload to caregiver burden was inconsistent, while the
   patient's mental state, drive, and age did not significantly impact
   caregiver burden. Discussion: Caregiver burden is influenced by a number
   of factors, but the negative appraisal of the situation by the caregiver
   is the key to assessing the amount of burden caregivers experience in
   caring for a stroke patient. Task oriented professional support reduces
   the workload of caregivers, but does not reduce their subjective burden.
   Caregivers need additional psychosocial support in order to cope with
   their role.},
